[src:corliss-steam-engine/7-south-stone-mill-drive] The building is located at the fourth privilege on Mother Brook and was used to make a variety of products in the 19th century, including copper cents, paper, cotton, wool, carpets, and handkerchiefs.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/7-south-stone-mill-drive] In the 1780s another mill, connected by the same wheel, was constructed on the site to produce wire for the new nation's nascent textile industry.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/7-south-stone-mill-drive] The first mill on this site burned in 1809, but was rebuilt with a new raceway and foundation.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/7-south-stone-mill-drive] The second mill began producing nails in 1814, and five years later its owner, Ruggles Whiting of Boston, sold it to the owner of the first mill, George Bird, who began using the whole site to manufacture paper.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/7-south-stone-mill-drive] In 1823 it switched to cotton, using the machinery of the former Norfolk Cotton Company.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/7-south-stone-mill-drive] It stands today, and was converted into a condominium complex in 1986–87.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/7-south-stone-mill-drive] Unlike the other mills, which were constructed in a strictly utilitarian style, this factory boasted a date stone reading "1835" and a dome-roofed cupola over the mill bell.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/7-south-stone-mill-drive] Together they stood as a testament to the primacy of the mills in the neighborhood.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/7-south-stone-mill-drive] The mill at the fourth privilege, under the ownership of Bussey and with his agent, George H.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/7-south-stone-mill-drive] Kuhn, was among the first to install water-powered broad looms.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/7-south-stone-mill-drive] The looms enabled raw wool to enter the mills, be spun into thread, and then weaved into finished fabric, all under a single roof.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/7-south-stone-mill-drive] During the lunch break at the Cochrane Mill, a fire broke out on April 4, 1911 that quickly engulfed the mill.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/7-south-stone-mill-drive] There were 25 employees inside, including one who was taking a nap.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/7-south-stone-mill-drive] Another fire broke out in the mill on May 2, 1984.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/7-south-stone-mill-drive] This time, the mill was owned by the United Waste Company.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Steam power has generally been superseded by the internal combustion engine or by electrical power drawn from an electrical grid.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The only steam installations that are in widespread use are the highly efficient thermal power plants used for generating electricity on a large scale.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In contrast, the proposed steam engines may be for stationary, road, rail, or marine use.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Although most references to "Modern Steam" apply to developments since the 1970s, certain aspects of advanced steam technology can be discerned throughout the 20th century, notably automatic boiler control along with rapid startup.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In 1922, Abner Doble developed an electro-mechanical system that reacted simultaneously to steam temperature and pressure, starting and stopping the feed pumps whilst igniting and cutting out the burner according to boiler pressure.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The contraflow monotube boiler had a working pressure of 750–1,200 psi (5.17–8.27 MPa) but contained so little water in circulation as to present no risk of explosion.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This type of boiler was continuously developed in the US, Britain and Germany throughout the 1930s and into the 1950s for use in cars, buses, trucks, railcars, shunting locomotives (US; switchers), a speedboat and, in 1933, a converted Travel Air 2000 biplane.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In the UK, Sentinel Waggon Works developed a vertical water-tube boiler running at 275 psi (1.90 MPa) which was used in road vehicles, shunting locomotives and railcars.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Steam could be raised much more quickly than with a conventional locomotive boiler.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Trials of the Anderson condensing system took place on Britain's Southern Railway between 1930 and 1935.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Anderson condensing system uses a process known as mechanical vapor recompression.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] It was devised by a Glasgow marine engineer, Harry Percival Harvey Anderson.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The theory was that, by removing around 600 of the 970 British thermal units present in each pound of steam (1400 of the 2260 kilojoules in each kilogram), it would be possible to return the exhaust steam to the boiler by a pump which would consume only 1–2% of the engine's power output.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Between 1925 and 1927 Anderson, and another Glasgow engineer John McCullum (some sources give McCallum), conducted experiments on a stationary steam plant with encouraging results.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A company, Steam Heat Conservation (SHC), was formed and a demonstration of Anderson's system was arranged at Surbiton Electricity Generating Station.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] SHC was interested in applying the system to a railway locomotive and contacted Richard Maunsell of the Southern Railway.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell requested that a controlled test be carried out at Surbiton and this was done about 1929.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell's technical assistant, Harold Holcroft, was present and a fuel saving of 29% was recorded, compared to conventional atmospheric working.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Southern Railway converted SECR N class locomotive number A816 (later 1816 and 31816) to the Anderson system in 1930.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive underwent trials and initial results were encouraging.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The trials continued until 1934 but various problems arose, mostly with the fan for forced draught, and the project went no further.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive was converted back to standard form in 1935.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The work of French mechanical engineer André Chapelon in applying scientific analysis and a strive for thermal efficiency was an early example of advanced steam technology.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Chapelon's protégé Livio Dante Porta continued Chapelon's work.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Postwar in the late 1940s and 1950s some designers worked on modernising steam locomotives.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Argentinian engineer Livio Dante Porta in the development of Stephensonian railway locomotives incorporating advanced steam technology was a precursor of the 'Modern Steam' movement from 1948.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Where possible, Porta much preferred to design new locomotives, but more often in practice he was forced to radically update old ones to incorporate the new technology.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] 1949 by Oliver Bulleid and the British Rail ‘Standard’ class steam locomotives of the 1950s by Robert Riddles, particularly the BR Standard Class 9F, were used to trial new steam locomotive design features, including the Franco-Crosti boiler.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] On moving to Ireland, Bulleid also designed CIÉ No.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Sir Biscoe Tritton Lecture, given by Roger Waller, of the DLM company to the Institute of Mechanical Engineers in 2003 gives an idea of how problems in steam power are being addressed.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Waller refers mainly to some rack and pinion mountain railway locomotives that were newly built from 1992 to 1998.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] They were developed for three companies in Switzerland and Austria and continued to work on two of these lines as of 2008.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The new steam locomotives burn the same grade of light oil as their diesel counterparts, and all demonstrate the same advantages of ready availability and reduced labour cost; at the same time, they have been shown to greatly reduce air and ground pollution.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Their economic superiority has meant that they have largely replaced the diesel locomotives and railcars previously operating the line; additionally, steam locomotives are a tourist attraction.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A parallel line of development was the return to steam power of the old Lake Geneva paddle steamer *Montreux* that had been refitted with a diesel-electric engine in the 1960s.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Economic aims similar to those achieved with the rack locomotives were pursued through automatic control of the light-oil-fired boiler and remote control of the engine from the bridge, enabling the steamship to be operated by a crew of the same size as a motor ship.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A power unit based on advanced steam technology burning fossil fuel will inevitably emit carbon dioxide, a long-lasting greenhouse gas.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] However, significant reductions of other pollutants such as CO and NOx are achievable by steam compared to other combustion technologies, since it does not involve explosive combustion, thus removing the need for add-ons (such as filters) or special preparation of fuel.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] If renewable fuel such as wood or other biofuel is used then the system could be carbon neutral.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The use of biofuel remains controversial; however, liquid biofuels are easier to manufacture for steam plant than for diesels as they do not demand the stringent fuel standards required to protect diesel injectors.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In principle, combustion and power delivery of steam plant can be considered separate stages.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] High overall thermal efficiency may be difficult to achieve, largely due to the extra stage of generating a working fluid between combustion and power delivery attributable mainly to leakages and heat losses.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The separation of the processes allows specific problems to be addressed at each stage without revising the whole system every time.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] For instance, the boiler or steam generator can be adapted to use any heat source, whether obtained from solid, liquid or gaseous fuel, and can use waste heat.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Whatever the choice, it will have no direct effect on the design of the engine unit, as that only ever has to deal with steam.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This project mainly includes combined electrical generation and heating systems for private homes and small villages burning wood or bamboo chips.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This is intended to replace 2-stroke donkey engines and small diesel power plants.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Drastic reduction in noise level is one immediate benefit of a steam-powered small plant.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Ted Pritchard, of Melbourne, Australia, was intensively developing this type of unit from 2002 until his death in 2007.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company Pritchard Power (now Uniflow Power) stated in 2010 that they continue to develop the stationary S5000, and that a prototype had been built and was being tested, and designs were being refined for market ready products.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Until 2006 a German company called *Enginion* was actively developing a *Steamcell*, a micro CHP unit about the size of a PC tower for domestic use.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] It seems that by 2008 it had merged with Berlin company AMOVIS.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Since 2012, a French company, EXOES, is selling to industrial firms a Rankine Cycle, patented, engine, which is designed to work with many fuels such as concentrated solar power, biomass, or fossil.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The system, called "SHAPE" for Sustainable Heat And Power Engine, converts the heat into electricity.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The SHAPE engine is suitable for embedded, and stationary, applications.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A SHAPE engine has been integrated into a biomass boiler, and into a Concentrated solar power system.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company is planning to work with automobile manufactures, long-haul truck manufactures, and railway corporations.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A similar unit is marketed by Powertherm, a subsidiary of Spilling (see below).
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A company in India manufactures steam-powered generators in a range of sizes from 4 hp to 50 hp.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] They also offer a number of different mills that can be powered by their engines.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In matter of technology, notice that the Quasiturbine is a uniflow rotary steam engine where steam intakes in hot areas, while exhausting in cold areas.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Spilling company produces a variety of small fixed stationary plant adapted to biomass combustion or power derived from waste heat or pressure recovery.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Finnish company Steammotor Finland has developed a small rotary steam engine that runs with 800 kW steam generator.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The engines are planned to produce electricity in wood chip fired power plants.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] According to the company, the steam engine named *Quadrum* generates 27% efficiency and runs with 180 °C steam at 8 bar pressure, while a corresponding steam turbine produces just 15% efficiency, requires steam temperature of 240 °C and pressure of 40 bar.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The high efficiency comes from a patented crank mechanism, that gives a smooth, pulseless torque.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company believes that by further developing the construction there is potential to reach as high efficiency as 30–35%.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] During the first 1970s oil crisis, a number of investigations into steam technology were initiated by large automobile corporations although as the crisis died down, impetus was soon lost.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Australian engineer Ted Pritchard's main field of research from the late 1950s until the 1970s was the building of several efficient steam power units working on the uniflow system adapted to a small truck and two cars.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] One of the cars was achieving the lowest emissions figures of that time.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] All these engines made heavy use of flameless ceramic heat cells both for the steam generator and at strategic boost points where steam was injected into the cylinder(s).
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A design mounted on power bogies with compact water-tube boiler similar to Sentinel designs of the 1930s.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Example: Sentinel-Cammell locomotive (right).
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Both 52 8055 and the proposed 5AT are of conventional layout, with the cab at the back, while the ACE 3000 had the cab located at the front.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Other approaches are possible, especially with liquid fuel firing.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This is a well-tried design with the potential for a large power output and would provide the driver good visibility.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Another well-tried design with large power potential.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A future design could include shorter water tanks, and a cab at each end, to give the driver a good view in either direction.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Another proposal for advanced steam technology is to revive the fireless locomotive, which runs on stored steam independently pre-generated.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] An example is the Solar Steam Train project in Sacramento, California.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The first **Allis-Chalmers Company** was formed in 1901 as an amalgamation of the Edward P.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Allis Company (steam engines and mill equipment), Fraser & Chalmers (mining and ore milling equipment), the Gates Iron Works (rock and cement milling equipment), and the industrial business line of the Dickson Manufacturing Company (engines and compressors).
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] It was reorganized in 1912 as the **Allis-Chalmers Manufacturing Company**.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] During the next 70 years, its industrial machinery filled countless mills, mines, and factories around the world, and its brand gained fame among consumers mostly from its farm equipment business's orange tractors and silver combine harvesters.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In the 1980s-1990s, a series of divestitures transformed the firm and eventually dissolved it.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Its successors are Allis-Chalmers Energy and AGCO.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Author-photographer Randy Leffingwell (1993) aptly summarized the firm's origins and character.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] He observed that it "grew by acquiring and consolidating the innovations" of various smaller firms and building upon them; and he continued that "Metal work and machinery were the common background.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Allis was an entrepreneur who in 1860 bought a bankrupt firm at a sheriff's auction, the Reliance Works of Milwaukee, Wisconsin, which had been owned by James Decker and Charles Seville.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Decker & Seville were millwrights who made equipment for flour milling.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Thomas Chalmers was a Scottish immigrant to America who came to the U.S. about 1842.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] By 1844 he was at Chicago, Illinois and had found work with P.W.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Gates, whose foundry and blacksmithing shops produced plows, wagons, and flour-milling equipment.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The Gates firm "built the first steam-operated sawmill in the country at a time when Chicago was the leading producer of milled lumber in the country." In 1872, Thomas Chalmers founded the Fraser & Chalmers firm to manufacture mining machinery, boilers, and pumps.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] By 1880 steam engines were part of the product line and by 1890, the firm had become one of the world's largest manufacturers of mining equipment.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Thomas Chalmers's son, William James Chalmers, was president of the company from circa 1890 to 1901.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Meanwhile, the Gates Iron Works, with Chalmers family involvement, had become a manufacturer of crushers, pulverizers, and other rock and cement milling equipment.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Another Scottish immigrant family, the Dickson family, came to Canada and the U.S. in the 1830s.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] By 1852, they had organized a small machine shop and foundry (Dickson & Company) in Scranton, Pennsylvania.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1856 Thomas Dickson became its president, and in 1862 the firm incorporated as the Dickson Manufacturing Company.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] By 1900 they were building boilers, steam engines, locomotives, internal combustion engines, blowers, and air compressors.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Allis, Fraser & Chalmers, and Gates firms had decided to merge their companies.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Edwin Reynolds believed Allis could control the industrial engine business.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In May 1901 the Allis-Chalmers Company was formed.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] It acquired Dickson's industrial engine business.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Dickson's locomotive business was rolled into the new locomotive consolidation, the American Locomotive Company (ALCO).
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The managing director of the new company was Charles Allis, his brother William was chairman of the board, and William J.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Shortly after the merger was completed, a new factory was built in an area west of Milwaukee that was then known as North Greenfield.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1902, with this new factory, the locale was renamed West Allis, Wisconsin.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Like other firms that build capital equipment for industrial corporations, it also supplied consulting, erecting, and training services, such as helping a mining company to design a plant, to build its buildings and set up its machinery, and to teach the employees how to use and maintain it.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1903, Allis-Chalmers acquired the Bullock Electric Company of Cincinnati, Ohio, which added steam turbines to Allis-Chalmers's powerplant equipment business line.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] By 1912, the Allis-Chalmers Company was in financial trouble, so it was reorganized.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] It was renamed the Allis-Chalmers Manufacturing Company, and Otto Falk, a former Brigadier General of the Wisconsin National Guard, was appointed to turn it around.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Falk pushed for new products and new or expanded markets.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Falk saw great growth potential in the mechanization of agriculture, which at the time was blossoming all over America.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Allis-Chalmers's first farm tractors, the 10-18, the Model 6-12, and the Model 15-30, were developed and marketed between 1914 and 1919, and the farm implement line was expanded.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] As had also been true of the 1900–1920 period, the Roaring Twenties were a favorable time for consolidation and even conglomeration throughout the business world.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] It was also a time of strongly continuing mechanization on North American farms.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] At Allis-Chalmers, the 1920s brought yet more tractors, such as the 18-30, the 12-20, the 15-25, and the United tractor/Model U.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Famed inventor and engineer Nikola Tesla spent the period 1919-1922 working in Milwaukee for Allis-Chalmers.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1926 Falk hired Harry Merritt, who would be a senior executive in Allis-Chalmers's tractor business for many years.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Merritt had worked in the sales and marketing of various brands of farm and construction equipment, most recently Holt, when Falk hired him away.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Buescher, who worked under Merritt, credited Merritt with turning around Allis-Chalmers's ailing farm equipment business and transforming it into the main profit center for the parent corporation.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] He said, "Some say that General Falk pulled Harry Merritt into Milwaukee to liquidate the ailing tractor division.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Others say that he was brought in to breathe new life into the moribund and unprofitable operation.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Even if the first appraisal is correct, the second proved to be the way it turned out. […] After Merritt's arrival, the profit picture changed.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Also in 1926, Allis-Chalmers acquired Nordyke Marmon & Company of Indianapolis, Indiana, a maker of flour-milling equipment.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1927, it acquired the Pittsburgh Transformer Company, a maker of electrical transformers.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1928, Allis-Chalmers acquired the Monarch Tractor Company of Springfield, Illinois, thus adding a line of crawler tractors.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1929, it acquired the La Crosse Plow Works of La Crosse, Wisconsin.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The La Crosse Plow Works had a good-quality plow and various desirable implements, which now expanded the Allis-Chalmers implement line.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Also in 1929, Harry Merritt was in California when the bright orange California poppy blossoms inspired him to think about the use of bright colors in marketing.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Brightly colored things that can be seen from far away had potential in farm equipment marketing.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] He soon changed the paint color of Allis-Chalmers's tractors to Persian Orange, the available paint color that he felt most closely resembled the California poppy's color.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Thus began the tradition of orange Allis-Chalmers tractors.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Various competitors would follow suit over the next decade, as International Harvester switched to all-red (1936), Minneapolis-Moline switched to Prairie Gold (late 1930s), and Case switched to Flambeau Red (late 1930s).
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] John Deere already had a distinctive color scheme with its bright green and yellow.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1928, Henry Ford canceled U.S. production of the Fordson tractor.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Many of these firms formed a conglomerate in 1928 called the United Tractor & Equipment corporation.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] United arranged a deal with Allis-Chalmers to build a tractor to substitute for the now-missing Fordson.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Around 1930, the United conglomerate collapsed.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The reasons that various authors have given have been disagreements between its investors, the onset of the Great Depression, and the fact that Ford Motor Company Ltd of England, which was continuing the Fordson line independently of the U.S.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Ford company, began exporting new Fordsons to America.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The United tractor became the Allis-Chalmers Model U.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Despite the Great Depression, Allis-Chalmers succeeded as demand for its machinery continued.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1931, it acquired Advance-Rumely of La Porte, Indiana, mostly because Merritt wanted the company's network of 24 branch houses and about 2,500 dealers, which would greatly increase Allis-Chalmers's marketing and sales power in the farm equipment business.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Also in 1931, the corporation's electrical equipment business expanded via acquisition when Brown, Boveri & Cie, in a financial pinch because of the Depression, sold its U.S. electrical operations to Allis-Chalmers.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] After 1931 Allis-Chalmers was the licensee for U.S. sales of European products of Brown, Boveri & Cie.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1932, Allis-Chalmers collaborated with Firestone to introduce pneumatic rubber tires to tractors.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The innovation quickly spread industry-wide, as (to many farmers' surprise) it improved tractive force and fuel economy in the range of 10% to 20%.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Within only 5 years, pneumatic rubber tires had displaced cleated steel wheels across roughly half of all tractors sold industry-wide.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Cleated steel remained optional equipment into the 1940s.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Also in 1932, Allis-Chalmers acquired the Ryan Manufacturing Company, which added various grader models to its construction equipment line.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1933, Allis-Chalmers introduced its Model WC, its first-generation row-crop tractor, which would become its highest-selling tractor ever.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1937, its lighter and more affordable second-generation row-crop, the Model B, arrived, and also became a top seller.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Its All-Crop Harvester was the market leader in pull-type (tractor-drawn) combine harvesters.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In October 1937, Allis-Chalmers was one of fourteen major electrical manufacturing companies that went to court to change the way labor unions excluded contractors and products in the building trades through the union use of the "Men and Means Clause".
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The action of Allis-Chalmers and others eventually resulted in the U.S.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Supreme Court decision of June 18, 1945, that ended certain union practices that violated the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] World War II caused Allis-Chalmers, like most other manufacturing companies, to become extremely busy.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] As happened with many firms, its civilian product lines experienced a period of being "on hold", with emphasis on parts and service to keep existing machines running, but its war materiel production was pushed to the maximum of productivity and output.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In the late 1930s through mid-1940s, Allis-Chalmers made machinery for naval ships, such as Liberty ship steam engines, steam turbines, generators, and electric motors; artillery tractors and tractors for other army use; electrical switches and controls; and other products.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Allis-Chalmers was also one of many firms contracted to build equipment for the Manhattan Project.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Its experience in mining and milling machinery made it a logical choice for uranium mining and processing equipment.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Allis-Chalmers ranked 45th among United States corporations in the value of wartime military production contracts.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Immediately at the war's end, in 1945–1946, Allis-Chalmers endured a crippling 11-month labor strike.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Buescher was convinced that the corporation never entirely recovered from the effects of this strike.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] This seems debatable given the various successes that Allis-Chalmers did have during the next 30 years, including prosperity in the farm equipment business in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] But it certainly gave competitors a chance to grab market share.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] After WWII some companies refused to sell equipment to Japanese farmers.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Allis-Chalmers dealers did not hesitate to sell to these farmers so many farms to this day still have an Allis-Chalmers tractor in Oregon.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1948, the Model WC was improved with various new features and became the Model WD, another top seller.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] It included fully independent power take off, which was powered by a two clutch system.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] It also included power adjust rear wheels, which became an industry standard.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Production of this model continued into 1953, with nearly 150,000 tractors produced.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The 1950s were a time of great demand for more power in farm tractors, as well as greater capability from their hydraulic and electrical systems.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] It was also a decade of extensive dieselization, from railroad locomotives to farm tractors and construction equipment.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1953, Allis-Chalmers acquired the Buda Engine Company of Harvey, Illinois.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Allis wanted Buda for its line of diesel engines, because its previous supplier, Detroit Diesel, was a division of General Motors, whose recent acquisition of the Euclid heavy equipment company now made it a competitor of Allis-Chalmers for construction equipment business.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The Buda-Lanova models were re-christened the "Allis-Chalmers Diesel" engine line.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Diesel engineers were busy during the following years updating and expanding the line.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1952, the company acquired Laplant-Choate, which added various models of scrapers to its construction equipment line.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1953, the WD-45 was introduced, replacing the WD.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The motor was increased to 226 cubic inches, giving it 30 horsepower on the drawbar at the Nebraska Tests.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] This was almost double the horsepower of the WD.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] A new Allis chalmers designed Snap- Coupler hitch was used.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] It allowed the operator to hook up to an implement from the seat of the tractor.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] A Buda diesel-powered WD-45 was introduced in 1955.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] This series stayed in production until the unveiling of the D-series in 1957.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1955, the company acquired Gleaner Manufacturing Company, which was an important move for its combine harvester business.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Allis was the market leader in pull-type (tractor-drawn) combines, with its All-Crop Harvester line.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] But acquiring Gleaner meant that it would now also be a leader in self-propelled machines, and it would own two of the leading brands in combines.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The Gleaner line augmented (and later superseded) the All-Crop Harvester line, and for several years Gleaner's profits made up nearly all of Allis-Chalmers' profit.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Gleaners continued to be manufactured at the same factory, in Independence, Missouri, after the acquisition.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1957, the Allis-Chalmers D Series of tractors was introduced.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] It enjoyed great success over the next decade.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1959, Allis-Chalmers acquired the French company Vendeuvre.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Also in 1959, it acquired Tractomotive Corporation of Deerfield, Illinois, which it had been partnering with as an auxiliary equipment supplier for at least a decade.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In Haycraft's history of the construction equipment business (2000), he expressed the view that Allis-Chalmers relied too heavily for too long on partnering with auxiliary equipment suppliers, and acquiring them, instead of investing in in-house product development.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In his view, this strategy limited the company's success in this business, and it eventually had to spend the development dollars anyway.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Buescher's comments about the Buda acquisition and the need for subsequent improvement of its designs seem to corroborate this view.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] However, the topic is multivariate and complex; elsewhere in his memoir, Buescher presents a viewpoint in which investing in research and product development is an expensive move that often does not pay off for the innovator and mostly benefits competitor clones.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1960, the U.S. government uncovered an attempt to form a cartel in the heavy electric equipment industry.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] It charged 13 companies, including the largest in the industry (Westinghouse, General Electric, and Allis-Chalmers), with price fixing and bid rigging.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Most feigned innocence, but Allis-Chalmers pleaded guilty.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The D series continued to be successful in the 1960s.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The factory-installed turbocharger on the D19 was the first in the industry.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] It was soon followed by the 190 and the 190 XT, which was a direct competitor for the John Deere Model 4020 with 98 horsepower (factory rating).
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1965, Allis-Chalmers acquired Simplicity for its line of lawn and garden equipment.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Also in that year, the nuclear reactor SAFARI-1, a research reactor built by Allis-Chalmers, went into operation.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In the 1960s, the farm equipment, construction equipment, and heavy electrical industries were not as profitable for Allis-Chalmers as they had been in the 1930s through 1950s.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Reasonable prosperity continued in the farm equipment line, but the economics of all the industries shifted toward greater uncertainty and brittler success for firms that didn't become number one or two in a field.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Allis-Chalmers was often number three or four, as Deere and International Harvester led in farm machinery, Caterpillar and Case led in construction, and Westinghouse and General Electric led in heavy electric markets.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In the late 1960s, a trend of conglomeration flared, as mega-conglomerates like Ling-Temco-Vought, Gulf+Western, and White Consolidated Industries went on buying sprees.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Several takeover attempts by those firms were made on Allis-Chalmers.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] It was during the same era and business climate that Tenneco acquired Case.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1960, Allis-Chalmers built the first grate-kiln ore pellet plant at the Humboldt mine in Michigan.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The company eventually built about 50 such plants.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1974, Allis-Chalmers's construction equipment business was reorganized into a joint venture with Fiat, which bought a 65% majority stake at the outset.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In May 1975, the company closed its 20-acre, 78-year-old Pittsburgh North Side factory that employed close to 1,100 full-time and produced both distribution and instrument control transformers.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1977, to compete in the recently expanding market segment of compact diesel utility tractors (such as the Kubota line and the Ford 1000 and 1600 built by Shibaura), Allis-Chalmers began importing Hinomoto tractors with Toyosha diesel engines from Japan.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] They were rebadged with the Allis-Chalmers brand for U.S. sales.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1978, a joint venture with Siemens, Siemens-Allis, was formed, supplying electrical control equipment.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The company began to struggle in the 1980s in a climate of rapid economic change.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] It was forced amid financial struggles to sell major business lines.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1983, Allis-Chalmers sold Simplicity, the lawn and garden equipment division, to the division's management.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1988, Allis-Chalmers sold its American Air Filter filtration business (with 27 production facilities internationally and sales into 100-plus countries) for approximately $225 million to SnyderGeneral Corporation of Dallas, a leading global air quality control firm.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1990, Deutz-Allis was sold to its management and became Allis-Gleaner Corporation (AGCO).
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Tractors began selling under the AGCO-Allis name and were again painted Persian Orange.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The AGCO brand of orange tractors was produced until 2011 when AGCO announced that it was phasing out the brand.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1998, what remained of the Allis-Chalmers manufacturing businesses were divested, and in January 1999, the company officially closed its Milwaukee offices.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The remaining service businesses became Allis-Chalmers Energy in Houston, Texas.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In August 2008, Briggs & Stratton announced that it would sell lawn tractors under the Allis-Chalmers brand name.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Allis-Chalmers offered a complete line of agricultural machinery, from tillage and harvesting to tractors.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1959, a team led by Harry Ihrig built a 15 kW fuel cell tractor for Allis-Chalmers which was demonstrated across the US at state fairs.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] This was the first fuel-cell-powered vehicle.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Potassium hydroxide served as the electrolyte.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The original AC fuel cell tractor is currently on display at the Smithsonian.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Below is a gallery showcasing some of the models that Allis-Chalmers produced throughout its history, most of which are painted in their distinctive orange paint.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The first model introduced in 1947 was called the "Roto-Baler" and the fore-runner of modern round balers, albeit with much smaller bales.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The Roto-Baler had a production run from 1947 to 1964 and then again from 1972 to 1974.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Allis Chalmers also built many small square baler models.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Allis-Chalmers originally developed their pull-type "all-crop harvester" as their solution for growers to harvest their crops beginning in 1933.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1955, Allis-Chalmers acquired the Gleaner Baldwin/Gleaner Manufacturing Company and its line of self-propelled combine harvesters.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Allis Chalmers marketed a full line of Industrial and Power House equipment, including turbo generators and medium voltage switchgear.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In the 1920s through the 1960s AC Power House and Industrial equipment was competitive with industry giants like General Electric and Westinghouse.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] As early as the 1920s AC was manufacturing multi MVA hydro-electric generators and turbines, many of which remain in service (Louisville Gas & Electric Ohio Falls units 1–8, 8MW low head turbines and Kentucky Utilities Dix Dam units 1–3, 11MVA 300 RPM generators).
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Allis Chalmers manufactured several lines of medium voltage switchgear, such as the HF and MA lines.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The HF line competed with the General Electric "AM" Magneblast line of vertical-lift medium-voltage switchgear.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The MA line was a competitor of the ITE "HK" line of horizontal-racking medium-voltage switchgear.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Allis-Chalmers produced a line of substation transformers, voltage regulators, and distribution transformers.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1965, Allis-Chalmers built "Big Allis", or Ravenswood No.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] It is located in Queens, has an output of 1000 MW, and remains operational.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In the late 1960s and early 1970s AC expanded into lawn and out-door equipment.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] AC made a line of 6-wheeled Amphibious ATV's called the "Terra Tiger".
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] In 1965, Allis-Chalmers built hydrogen fueled fuel cell golf carts.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] Allis-Chalmers Energy was a Houston-based multi-faceted oilfield services company.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] The company provided services and equipment to oil and natural gas exploration and production companies, both domestically and internationally.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/allis-chalmers] It became Archer in 2011 after it merged with Seawell, another oil services/energy company.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] The **Antique Gas & Steam Engine Museum** (**AGSEM**) is a living history museum founded in 1969.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] It is located on 55 acres (220,000 m2) of county-owned land at 2040 N Santa Fe Ave. on the outskirts of Vista, California.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] The museum is a non-profit 501c(3) organization, run by several paid employees along with volunteer help.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] The museum is open almost every day of the year and has two bi-annual shows, on the 3rd and 4th weekends of June and October.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] The museum also has other public and private events throughout the year.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] Gas Engine Row has many large stationary gas engines from the early 1900s.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] Almost all of the engines on Gas Engine Row can be seen running during the shows.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] Steam Engine Row showcases many different types and sizes of stationary steam engines; from a monstrous 300 horsepower (220 kW) Allis Chalmers Corliss engine with a 12-foot-diameter (3.7 m) flywheel, to a small J.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] They are all powered by steam from two large boilers, nicknamed Pat and Rich, after two long-time museum volunteers who maintain and operate them.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] There are six operational steam traction engines on the grounds, with a 1913 Buffalo-Pitts steamroller and a 1909 20 horsepower Case undergoing restoration.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] The operational steam tractors are an 1895 Russell & Co.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] Case 60 horsepower (45 kW) steam tractor, a 1920 Minneapolis 20 horsepower (15 kW) steam tractor, and a 1916 15-30 Russell & Co.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] Most, if not all, of these tractors can be seen steaming around the grounds during the show days.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] The museum is also home to a large number of old tractors.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] Two D8 Caterpillars, a D9, a few large 1930s Caterpillars, some Best crawlers and many other examples of tracked tractors can be seen at the museum.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] The typical tractors such as Farmall, John Deere, Oliver, and Allis-Chalmers can be seen out at the museum, but there are more than a few rarer examples too.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] There is a 1924 Buffalo-Springfield road roller, a gigantic 1918 30-60 Aultman-Taylor gas tractor, a 1911 Fairbanks-Morse 15-25 kerosene tractor, a 1915 International Harvester Mogul 8-16, several Rumely Oil-Pulls, and many more.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] There is an operational blacksmith shop with an operating line shaft setup powered by a 15-horsepower 1917 Mogul gasoline engine.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] During the show days, there are multiple forges lit, and multiple blacksmiths can be found working pieces of iron into many different things.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] Also located on museum grounds is the Short Track Model Railroad Club, featuring an NTrak model railroad with trains traveling through more than 40 modules, including a drive-in movie theater, a fairgrounds, farms, towns, and a coal mine and other scenes.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] The Short Track, N-Scale, Model Railroad club is an educational organization that seeks to further the appreciation of railroad history in the United States.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] Many members are also National Model Railroad Association (NMRA) members and a few have earned the title of "Master Modeler." Their Donner Pass, N-scale, model railroad exhibit shows the Southern Pacific crossing of the Sierra Mountains between Colfax, CA and West Reno, NV.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] There is also a small layout that can be operated by children (The Young & Victorious RR).
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] The Museum Weavers are housed in a 4,000-square-foot (370 m2) barn, featuring more than 50 working looms for weaving.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] Members of this club meet weekly to learn and practice weaving, rug-making and rope-making.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] The working gristmill grinds wheat and corn into flour, which is available for sale during the twice-yearly shows.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] During the summer months, the museum grows sorghum cane, which is made into molasses for the fall show.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] The Sawmill is run by a D-3000 Cat diesel engine, Hawthorne Machinery in San Diego provided the cylinder liners.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] The Sawmill was re-assembled and improved following a donation from the Pederson Brothers who had operated it in the Big Bear area years ago.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/antique-gas-and-steam-engine-museum] This is likely the only Sawmill that can be seen operating in San Diego County.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf left Cornwall in 1785 to work for Joseph Bramah's engineering works in London.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] He worked there and at other firms as an engineer and engine builder until 1811 experimenting with high pressure steam and a much improved boiler.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] Michael Loam, who introduced the man engine to the UK, was trained by him.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] When he returned to Cornwall, beam engine designs were crude, shackled by outdated Watt patents and poor engineering, struggling to compete with large water wheels, even used underground.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] He learned from Bramah that to move forward meant adopting much improved engineering techniques, for it was Bramah who invented quality control.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf was chief engineer to Harvey & Co of Hayle, the leading engineering and foundry works, at this time the largest in the world.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] They eventually swallowed up the rival Copperhouse Foundry run by Sandys, Carne and Vivian.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] For very many years they were the leading firm worldwide for drainage engines, even supplying three eight-beamed pumping engines to the Dutch government to drain the Haarlemmermeer (see Museum De Cruquius).
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] By the time Woolf retired in 1836 the Cornish engine, owing largely to his efforts, was a thing of magnificent beauty and efficiency.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] In 1803, Woolf obtained a patent on an improved boiler for producing high pressure steam.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] In 1804, he patented his best-known invention, a compound steam engine.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf's engine was a parallel compound engine with two cylinders in which the steam worked in succession.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] These were both coupled to the same end of the beam of the engine.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] The operation of the engine can be described as being a high-pressure cylinder of Trevithick's high-pressure simple expansion engine, followed by a condensing cylinder of Watt's design.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf had worked as an engine erector for Hornblower and was familiar with his earlier work on compound engines.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] As a Cornishman, he was also familiar with Trevithick and his newly developed high-pressure 'puffer' engines that were then entering service.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] He recognised that, even with the new principle of expansion, the exhaust from a Trevithick engine was still of a pressure comparable to the inlet pressure of a Watt engine.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] From this step, it was a relatively simple matter to couple the two.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] For most uses, the cylinders of the engine were double-acting.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] Opposing sides of the high- and low-pressure cylinders were cross-connected to each other.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] Where engines were used for pumping, Woolf engines were also built with paired single-acting cylinders.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] Examples of Woolf compound rotative beam engines may be seen at Abbey Pumping Station, Blagdon Lake, Claymills Pumping Station, The Hamilton Museum of Steam & Technology, and the Western Springs Pumphouse, now part of the Museum of Transport and Technology Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A **high pressure watertube boiler** (also spelled *water-tube* and *water tube*) is a type of boiler in which water circulates in tubes heated externally by fire.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Fuel is burned inside the furnace, creating hot gas which boils water in the steam-generating tubes.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In smaller boilers, additional generating tubes are separate in the furnace, while larger utility boilers rely on the water-filled tubes that make up the walls of the furnace to generate steam.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The heated water/steam mixture then rises into the steam drum.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Here, saturated steam is drawn off the top of the drum.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In some services, the steam passes through tubes in the hot gas path (a superheater) to become superheated.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Superheated steam is a dry gas and therefore is typically used to drive turbines, since water droplets can severely damage turbine blades.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Saturated water at the bottom of the steam drum returns to the lower drum via large-bore 'downcomer tubes', where it pre-heats the feedwater supply.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] (In large utility boilers, the feedwater is supplied to the steam drum and the downcomers supply water to the bottom of the waterwalls).
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] To increase economy of the boiler, exhaust gases are also used to pre-heat combustion air blown into the burners, and to warm the feedwater supply in an economizer.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Such watertube boilers in thermal power stations are also called *steam generating units*.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The older fire-tube boiler design, in which the water surrounds the heat source and gases from combustion pass through tubes within the water space, is typically a much weaker structure and is rarely used for pressures above 2.4 MPa (350 psi).
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A significant advantage of the watertube boiler is that there is less chance of a catastrophic failure: there is not a large volume of water in the boiler nor are there large mechanical elements subject to failure.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A water-tube boiler was patented by Blakey of England in 1766 and was made by Dallery of France in 1780.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] "The ability of watertube boilers to be designed without the use of excessively large and thick-walled pressure vessels makes these boilers particularly attractive in applications that require dry, high-pressure, high-energy steam, including steam turbine power generation".
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Besides, they are frequently employed in power generation plants where large quantities of steam (ranging up to 500 kg/s) having high pressures i.e. approximately 16 megapascals (160 bar) and high temperatures reaching up to 550 °C are generally required.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] For example, the Ivanpah solar-power station uses two Rentech Type-D watertube boilers for plant warmup, and when operating as a fossil-fueled power station.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Modern boilers for power generation are almost entirely water-tube designs, owing to their ability to operate at higher pressures.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Where process steam is required for heating or as a chemical component, then there is still a small niche for fire-tube boilers.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] One notable exception is in typical nuclear-power stations (Pressurized Water Reactors), where the steam generators are generally configured similar to firetube boiler designs.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In these applications the hot gas path through the "Firetubes" actually carries the very hot/high pressure primary coolant from the reactor, and steam is generated on the external surface of the tubes.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Their ability to work at higher pressures has led to marine boilers being almost entirely watertube.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This change began around 1900, and traced the adoption of turbines for propulsion rather than reciprocating (i.e. piston) engines – although watertube boilers were also used with reciprocating engines, and firetube boilers were also used in many marine turbine applications.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] There has been no significant adoption of water-tube boilers for railway locomotives.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A handful of experimental designs were produced, but none of them were successful or led to their widespread use.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most water-tube railway locomotives, especially in Europe, used the Schmidt system.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most were compounds, and a few uniflows.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Norfolk and Western Railway's *Jawn Henry* was an exception, because it used a steam turbine combined with an electric transmission.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Not successful and re-boilered with a conventional boiler.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A slightly more successful adoption was the use of hybrid water-tube/fire-tube systems.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] As the hottest part of a locomotive boiler is the firebox, it was an effective design to use water-tubes here and a conventional fire-tube boiler as an economiser (i.e. pre-heater) in the usual position.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] One famous example of this was the USA Baldwin 4-10-2 No.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Built as a compound with a boiler pressure of 2,400 kilopascals (350 psi) it successfully covered over 160,000 kilometres (100,000 mi) in service.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] After a year however, it became clear that any improvements were overwhelmed by the extra costs, and it was retired as a museum display at the Franklin Institute in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A series of twelve experimental locomotives were constructed at the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad's Mt.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Clare shops under the supervision of George H.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Emerson, but none of them were replicated in any numbers.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The only water-tube locomotive boiler used in any large numbers was the Brotan boiler, invented by Johann Brotan in Austria in 1902 and found sparsely throughout Europe, although Hungary had around 1,000 in service.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Like the Baldwin 60000, it combined a water-tube firebox with a fire-tube barrel.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Brotan's original characteristic was a long steam drum running *above* the main barrel, resembling a Flaman boiler in appearance.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] While traction engines were usually built with locomotive boiler as its frame, other types of steam road vehicles such as lorries and cars used a wide range of different boiler types.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Road transport pioneers Goldsworthy Gurney and Walter Hancock both used water-tube boilers in their steam carriages around 1830.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most undertype wagons used water-tube boilers.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Many manufacturers used variants of the vertical cross-tube boiler, including Atkinson, Clayton, Garrett and Sentinel.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Other types include the Clarkson 'thimble tube' and the Foden O-type wagon's pistol-shaped boiler.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Steam fire-engine makers such as Merryweather usually used water-tube boilers for their rapid steam-raising capacity.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Many steam cars used water-tube boilers, and the Bolsover Express company even made a water-tube replacement for the Stanley Steamer fire-tube boiler.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The 'D-type' is the most common type of small- to medium-sized boilers, similar to the one shown in the schematic diagram.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] It is used in both stationary and marine applications.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] It consists of a large steam drum vertically connected to a smaller water drum (a.k.a.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] "mud drum") via multiple steam-generating tubes.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These drums and tubes as well as the oil-fired burner are enclosed by water-walls - additional water-filled tubes spaced close together so as to prevent gas flow between them.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These water wall tubes are connected to both the steam and water drums, so that they act as a combination of preheaters and downcomers as well as decreasing heat loss to the boiler shell.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The M-type boilers were used in many US World War II warships including hundreds of *Fletcher*-class destroyers.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Three sets of tubes form the shape of an M, and create a separately fired superheater that allows better superheat temperature control.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In addition to the mud drum shown on a D-type boiler, an M-type has a water-screen header and a waterwall header at the bottom of the two additional rows of vertical tubes and downcomers.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The *low water content* boiler has a lower and upper header connected by watertubes that are directly impinged upon from the burner.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This is a "furnace-less" boiler that can generate steam and react quickly to changes in load.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Designed by the American firm of Babcock & Wilcox, this type has a single drum, with feedwater drawn from the bottom of the drum into a header that supplies inclined water-tubes.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The watertubes supply steam back into the top of the drum.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Furnaces are located below the tubes and drum.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This type of boiler was used by the Royal Navy's *Leander*-class frigates and in United States Navy New Orleans-class cruisers.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Stirling boiler has near-vertical, almost-straight watertubes that zig-zag between a number of steam and water drums.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Usually there are three banks of tubes in a "four drum" layout, but certain applications use variations designed with a different number of drums and banks.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] They are mainly used as stationary boilers, owing to their large size, although the large grate area does also encourage their ability to burn a wide range of fuels.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Originally coal-fired in power stations, they also became widespread in industries that produced combustible waste and required process steam.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Paper pulp mills could burn waste bark, sugar refineries their bagasse waste.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Named after its designers, the then Poplar-based Yarrow Shipbuilders, this type of three-drum boiler has three drums in a delta formation connected by watertubes.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The drums are linked by straight watertubes, allowing easy tube-cleaning.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This does, however, mean that the tubes enter the drums at varying angles, a more difficult joint to caulk.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Outside the firebox, a pair of cold-leg pipes between each drum act as downcomers.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Due to its three drums, the Yarrow boiler has a greater water capacity.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Hence, this type is usually used in older marine boiler applications.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Its compact size made it attractive for use in transportable power generation units during World War II.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In order to make it transportable, the boiler and its auxiliary equipment (fuel oil heating, pumping units, fans etc.), turbines, and condensers were mounted on wagons to be transported by rail.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The White-Forster type is similar to the Yarrow, but with tubes that are gradually curved.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This makes their entry into the drums perpendicular, thus simpler to make a reliable seal.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Thornycroft & Company, the Thornycroft type features a single steam drum with two sets of watertubes either side of the furnace.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These tubes, especially the central set, have sharp curves.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Apart from obvious difficulties in cleaning them, this may also give rise to bending forces as the tubes warm up, tending to pull them loose from the tubeplate and creating a leak.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] There are two furnaces, venting into a common exhaust, giving the boiler a wide base tapering profile.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In a forced circulation boiler, a pump is added to speed up the flow of water through the tubes.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] After about 1910, the **Baker valve gear** was the main competitor to Walschaerts valve gear for steam locomotives in the United States.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Strictly speaking it was not a valve gear but a variable expansion mechanism adapted to the Walschaerts layout replacing the expansion link and sliding die block.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The Baker arrangement used more pivot bearings or *pin joints*, but avoided the die slip inherent to the expansion link, with the aim of lessening wear and the need for service; it could also facilitate longer valve travel.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] In the early 1900s there were many efforts to create a new valve gear to replace the by-then-standard Walschaerts valve gear.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] In the United States the Young, Southern, Caprotti and Franklin patterns were used on a few classes, but only the Baker pattern won more than limited acceptance.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Baker Company, of Swanton, Ohio; a builder of steam traction engines.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The idea came from an employee called Gifford but was developed by the Baker company with the first patents being issued in 1903 and with patents issued through at least November, 1912.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The Baker Locomotive Valve Gear was produced by the Pilliod Co. of Swanton, Ohio.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Subsequent versions were produced up to the end of steam service.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] It was particularly popular on the Norfolk and Western Railway, and almost all later N&W engines used it.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Other extensive users included the Chesapeake and Ohio Railway, the Nickel Plate Road, the New York Central Railroad and the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] There was always debate about the advantages of Baker gear, the main criticism being the number of pin joints and possible lost motion.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] While popular with railroads on the east, western states tended to continue with the Walschaerts pattern.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] In Britain, Baker gear was popular amongst model engineers but in full-size practice the length of the yoke and the width of the assembly may have been difficult to accommodate within the restricted loading gauge.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Other locomotives to use Baker valve gear were the New Zealand Railways J class, Ja class, Jb class, some Ka class, and the South Australian Railways 620 class.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The Baker valve gear replaces the expansion link of the Walschaerts gear with an assembly of levers and links which produces the same effect of allowing continuous variation valve travel.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The remainder of the gear is the same, so that the return crank and combination lever take the same form, although the proportions are usually modified.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The Pilliod Co. sold the gear as a single assembly which was mounted on the frame in the location ordinarily occupied by the Walschaerts expansion link.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The parts were arranged so that when the yoke was centered, the connection of the main link to the bellcrank was in a line with the two pivots on the yoke.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] At this point, the back and forth motion of the lower end of the main link left the top relatively motionless as main link swung back and forth on the swing links.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] In forward motion, the yoke was pushed forward, so that its upper pivot was in front of the bell crank-main link connection.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Moving the eccentric arm back and forth lowered and raised the top of the main link.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] This motion was translated by the bellcrank into back and forth motion of the radius rod.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The angle of the yoke controlled the relative motion, and therefore the cutoff; tilting the yoke backwards reversed the motion of the radius rod.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] A **Corliss steam engine** (or **Corliss engine**) is a steam engine, fitted with rotary valves and with variable valve timing patented in 1849, invented by and named after the US engineer George Henry Corliss of Providence, Rhode Island.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Corliss assumed the original invention from Frederick Ellsworth Sickels (1819- 1895), who held the patent (1829) in the US patent office.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Engines fitted with Corliss valve gear offered the best thermal efficiency of any type of stationary steam engine until the refinement of the uniflow steam engine and steam turbine in the 20th century.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Corliss engines were generally about 30 percent more fuel efficient than conventional steam engines with fixed cutoff.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] This increased efficiency made steam power more economical than water power, allowing industrial development away from millponds.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Corliss engines were typically used as stationary engines to provide mechanical power to line shafting in factories and mills and to drive dynamos to generate electricity.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Many were quite large, standing many metres tall and developing several hundred horsepower, albeit at low speed, turning massive flywheels weighing several tons at about 100 revolutions per minute.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Some of these engines have unusual roles as mechanical legacy systems and because of their relatively high efficiency and low maintenance requirements, some remain in service into the early 21st century.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] See, for example, the engines at the Hook Norton Brewery and the *Distillerie Dillon* in the list of operational engines.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Corliss engines have four valves for each cylinder, with steam and exhaust valves located at each end.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Corliss engines incorporate distinct refinements in both the valves themselves and in the valve gear, that is, the system of linkages that operate the valves.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] In contrast, conventional steam engines have a slide valve or piston valve that alternately feeds and exhausts through passages to each end of the cylinder.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] These passages are exposed to wide temperature swings during engine operation, and there are high temperature gradients within the valve mechanism.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Clark (1891) commented that the Corliss gear "is essentially a combination of elements previously known and used separately, affecting the cylinder and the valve-gear".
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] The origins of the Corliss gear with regard to previous steam valve gear was traced by Inglis (1868).
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] George Corliss received U.S. patent 6,162 for his valve gear on March 10, 1849.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] This patent covered the use of a *wrist-plate* to convey the valve motion from a single eccentric to the four valves of the engine, and it covered the use of trip valves with variable cutoff under governor control that characterize Corliss Engines.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Unlike later engines, most of which were horizontal, this patent describes a vertical cylinder beam engine, and it used individual slide valves for admission and exhaust at each end of the cylinder.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] The inlet valves are pulled open with an eccentric-driven pawl; when the pawl trips, the rapid closure is damped using a dashpot.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] In many engines, the same dashpot acts as a vacuum spring to pull the valves closed, but Corliss's early engines were slow enough that it was the weight of the dashpot piston and rod that closed the valve.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] The speed of a Corliss engine is controlled by varying the cutoff of steam during each power stroke, while leaving the throttle wide open at all times.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] To accomplish this, the centrifugal governor is linked to a pair of cams, one for each admission valve.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] These cams determine the point during the piston stroke that the pawl will release, allowing that valve to close.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] As with all steam engines where the cutoff can be regulated, the virtue of doing so lies in the fact that most of the power stroke is powered by the expansion of steam in the cylinder after the admission valve has closed.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] This comes far closer to the ideal Carnot cycle than is possible with an engine where the admission valve is open for the length of the power stroke and speed is regulated by a throttle valve.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] The Corliss valve gearing allowed more uniform speed and better response to load changes, making it suitable for applications like rolling mills and spinning, and greatly expanding its use in manufacturing.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Corliss valves open directly into the cylinder.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] The valves connect the cylinder to separate steam and exhaust plenums.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Initially, Corliss used slide valves with linear actuators, but by 1851, Corliss had shifted to semi-rotary valve actuators, as documented in U.S.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] In this engine, the wrist plate was moved to the center of the cylinder side, as on later Corliss engines.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] This was still a beam engine, however, and the semi-rotary valve actuators operated linear slide valves inside the four valve chests of the engine.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Corliss valves are in the form of a minor circular segment, rotating inside a cylindrical valve-face.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Their actuating mechanism is off along the axis of the valve, thus they have little "dead space" such as the stem of a poppet valve and the entire port area can be used efficiently for gas flow.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] As the area of a Corliss valve is small compared to the port area, the effects of gas flow generate relatively little torque on the valve axle compared to some other sorts of valve.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] These advantages have led to the Corliss form of valve being used in other roles, apart from steam engines with Corliss gear.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] The Rolls-Royce Merlin aero-engine used a rectangular butterfly valve as a throttle.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Gas-flow forces acting asymmetrically on this butterfly could lead to poor control of the power in some circumstances.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Late models, from the 134, used a Corliss throttle valve instead to avoid this problem.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] A common feature of large Corliss engines is one or two sets of narrow gear teeth in the rim of the flywheel.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] These teeth allow the flywheel to be *barred*, that is, turned with the aid of a crowbar.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] This may be needed during engine maintenance, for example, to set the cutoff and admission valve timing, and it may be needed during engine starting.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] The need for barring the engine during starting is most obvious on single-cylinder engines, where a careless engine operator might stop the engine with the piston in or near dead center.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Once stopped in this state, the engine cannot be started under its own power, so it must be barred to a more favorable position for starting.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Large Corliss engines cannot be safely started cold, so it is common to admit low-pressure steam to both sides of the cylinder to warm up the metalwork.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Turning the engine slowly during this process ensures that the entire engine is uniformly warmed, and it ensures that oil is uniformly distributed through the mechanism before applying power.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Again, barring may be used to do this, although operators sometimes do this by careful manual manipulation of the valves.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] For large engines, muscle powered barring is sufficiently difficult that *barring engines* are frequently installed.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] These are small engines with gear teeth cut to mate with the teeth on the flywheel.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Generally, the drive gears of the barring engine are designed to automatically disengage if the engine begins running under its own power while the barring gears are engaged.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] The Corliss Steam Engine Company was originally known as Fairbanks, Clark & Co. in the 1830s.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] In 1843 it was renamed Fairbanks, Bancroft & Co. when Edward Bancroft joined the company.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] In 1846 it was renamed Bancroft, Nightingale & Co. when George H.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Corliss joined the company, and in 1847 it was renamed Corliss, Nightingale and Co.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] In 1848 the company moved to the Charles Street Railroad Crossing in Providence, Rhode Island.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] In 1857 the company was renamed for the last time to Corliss Steam Engine Company.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] By 1864 Corliss bought out his partners and was the sole owner of the company.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] By 1859, all of the key features of what we now know as the Corliss engine were in place.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Patents granted to Corliss and others incorporated rotary valves and crank shafts in-line with the cylinders.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Competing inventors worked hard to invent alternatives to Corliss' mechanisms; they generally avoided Corlis's use of a wrist plate and adopted alternative releasing mechanisms for the steam valves, as in Jamieson's U.S.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Corliss' 1849 patent expired in 1870; the term of this patent had been extended by U.S.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Hick and Son were first to introduce the Corliss engine into the United Kingdom about 1864.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] After 1870, numerous other companies began to manufacture Corliss engines.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Harris Steam Engine Company, the Worthington Pump and Machinery Company, and Allis-Chalmers.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] In general, these machines were referred to as Corliss engines regardless of who made them.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] In 1895 the company was shut down under the burden of $800,000 debt, and in 1900 it was sold to International Power Company controlled by industrialist Joseph H.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] In 1905 it was transferred to another Hoadley's firm, the American & British Manufacturing Corporation.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] In 1925 the company merged into Franklin Machine Company.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] By then Franklin Machine Company was already owned by the William A.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] As of 2024 there are approximately six engines with the original slide-valve mechanisms still in existence, including one at 7 South Stone Mill Drive along Mother Brook in Dedham, Massachusetts.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] The Corliss Centennial Engine was an all-inclusive, specially built rotative beam engine that powered virtually all of the exhibits at the United States Centennial Exhibition in Philadelphia in 1876 through shafts totaling over a mile in length.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Grant and Emperor Pedro II of Brazil, the engine was in public view for the duration of the fair.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] The engine was configured as two cylinders side by side.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Each cylinder was bored to 44 inches (112 cm) with a stroke of 10 feet (3.0 m).
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] The Centennial Engine was 45 feet (14 m) tall, had a flywheel 30 feet (9.1 m) in diameter, and produced 1,400 horsepower (1,000 kW).
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] After the fair it was disassembled and shipped back to Corliss's plant in Providence.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] Seven years later it was sold and powered a Chicago factory owned by George Pullman until 1910, when it was sold as scrap.
[src:corliss-steam-engine/corliss-steam-engine] This engine became a cultural icon, so much so that to many modern historians the term **Corliss Engine** (or **Corliss Steam Engine**) refers to this specific engine and not to the broad class of engines fitted with Corliss valve gear.
